# Data Lake Operational Metrics as Registry+Spec \- Design

This document outlines the design for Polaris to serve as a collaborative operational metrics registry for Data Lake tables. In this approach, Polaris defines specifications for external services to submit and retrieve operational metric values, similar to how Policies are defined: their specification is stored in Polaris while implementation is delegated to query engines and external systems.

## Overview

Rather than computing metrics internally, Polaris acts as a centralized registry where:

1. **Polaris** defines the list of operational metrics that can be computed, submitted by and served to external services  
2. **Polaris** packages a reference implementation of metric calculation that can be used for small Iceberg tables, for illustrative purposes  
3. **Service administrators** plug their own metric computation method (e.g. leveraging query engines, maintenance systems, …)  
4. **Service administrators** grant metrics Read and Write permissions to external services via RBAC  
5. **Polaris** validates, stores, and serves metrics through an HTTP API  
6. **Service administrators** plug their preferred database for metrics storage, via specific extension points

This collaborative design allows Polaris to centralize Data Lake Operational Metrics while leveraging the distributed computing power of external services in the Data Lake ecosystem.

## Operational Metrics System

![][image1]

### RBAC

Similar to POLICY\_READ and POLICY\_WRITE, new roles must be defined to prevent unauthorized actors from reading and writing metrics:

1. OPERATIONAL\_METRICS\_WRITE \- Permission to submit operational metrics  
2. OPERATIONAL\_METRICS\_READ \- Permission to retrieve operational metrics

Much like other privileges, those can be granted on a catalog, a namespace or a table.

### Registry

The registry contains the list of supported operational metrics.  It defines the name and type of metrics that can be computed, pushed to and fetched from Polaris by external services and query engines.

The list of supported metrics is statically defined.  It may become dynamic in a subsequent phase.

### API

In order to distinguish the Operational Metrics API from the Iceberg REST API , while maintaining consistency, a new OpenAPI definition is created.  All Operational Metrics endpoints are located under `/api/operational-metrics`.  See the “API” document tab for the list of API endpoints.

### SPI

A Service Provider Interface is defined to allow service administrators to use their preferred database for metrics storage and retrieval.  This flexibility enables administrators to decide whether they want to keep all historical values in a time-series database, use custom retention policy, etc…

### Initial list of operational metrics

The following operational metrics list is supported by the first version of this proposal:

1. data-file-count \- Total number of data files in the table  
2. data-file-size-stats \- Data file size distribution statistics  
3. partition-count \- Number of distinct partitions  
4. partition-size-stats \- Partition size distribution statistics

### Metrics computation reference implementation

A separate module contains the code to compute the initial list of operational metrics for user-provided Iceberg tables.  It acts as an external service and connects to Polaris using the API endpoints defined in this document.

It can be run as a separate CLI tool.  Its role is to demonstrate how metrics flow into Polaris as well as provide an implementation that can be extended/improved by administrators to accommodate for larger tables or different table formats.

## Storage

Out of the box, a no-op SPI is used by Polaris.  I.e. unless an operational metric database is explicitly defined by an administrator, metrics support is effectively disabled.  Polaris does not enforce any specific database type or schema.

The Metrics database is assumed to be secured and trusted.  I.e. It is the administrators’ responsibility to ensure that metrics are only accessible to the Polaris service.

## Data Cleanup / Retention Policy

As storage is external to Polaris, it is the administrators’ responsibility to implement proper retention policies and data cleanup logic, possibly leveraging the Polaris Events API.

## Deployment model

The Operational Metrics system is integrated in the Polaris server.  Its API is deployed alongside other Polaris API (catalog, management) in the same Quarkus runtime.

## Data representation

### Point metrics

Certain metrics contain a single value (e.g. total number of files in a table, total number of partitions, …).  For those metrics, the storage format as well as the API response format is trivial: it is composed of the metric name and its value, as well as the timestamp of the last metric update.

### Histograms

Histograms inherently require more than a single data point.  For those metrics, the storage format consists in a series of percentiles, as well as the arithmetic average, the standard deviation and the total sum of all values.  The expected percentiles are: the minimum (p0), the 10th, 25th, median, 75th, 90th and 99th percentiles (p10, p25, p50, p75, p90, p99) as well as outliers percentiles and maximum value (p99.9, p99.99 and p100).

## Non-Iceberg tables

The operational metrics component may be able to compute a subset of metrics for non-iceberg tables.  Typically, for Generic Tables that are partitioned, it could be possible to compute the total number of partitions and the partition sizes statistics.  The same could also apply for Table Sources, should the proposal be accepted.
